share.share_text:
**long post warning**
Recently Iâve been talking with a lot of my mentors and friends about the meaning of why I (we) play music. As Iâve been practicing and listening more with that I mind Iâve found myself gravitating to more of Coltranes mid to late 60s recordings as well as some of the early 70s acid/modal jazz. Iâve found this music speaks to me in more ways than just saxophone technique or chops. Not that I donât love when people shred, nor do I want to stop trying to do that but Iâm realizing slowly that the notes donât even matter. Itâs the message and meaning behind them. In as little or as much as the player wants.
I know these realizations might sound clichÃ© but itâs been something that Iâve really been thinking about and wanted to share with all of you.
Iâve been practicing a lot with drones and trying to make my message/voice come across without thinking about the notes.
Thank you to @ulyssesowensjr_, @alain_bradette @lucasrobertopino, @thomasmilovac and many others that I donât have room to tag for helping me realize these things ð¥°
- Ryan
